<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by  the National Landlords Association</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by  the National Landlords Association</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Background:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The National Landlords Association (NLA) exists to protect and promote the interests of private residential landlords. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">With more than 20,000 individual landlords from around the United Kingdom and over 100 local authority associates, it provides a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">comprehensive range of benefits and services to its members and strives to raise standards in the private-rented sector.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NLA seeks a fair legislative and regulatory environment for the private-rented sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (PRS)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> while aiming to ensure that landlords </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are aware of their statutory rights and responsibilities.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 1:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">V</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">iews on new and innovative responses to the changes to housing support already taking place, which could help shape future approaches</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The work done by credit unions in creating Jam-Ja</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r accounts for tenants on Local Housing Allowance has been very beneficial for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">landlords </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tenants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by ring-fencing money in a tenant’s credit union account and only allowing it to be spent in a pre-agreed way. Therefore, for many tenants who t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ransit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ioned from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">system of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">direct payment of Housing benefit to landlords</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to the arrangements of payment to tenants under the LHA regime</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, these Jam-Jar accounts meant that it prevented them accidently spending the money allocated for the rent on other items</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Unfortunately</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, most credit unions charge for such accounts and awareness of their existence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">remains</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> low amongst both landlords and tenants. However, where landlords and tenants have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> used these schemes, anecdotal evidence suggests that incidents of rent a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rrears fall dramatically.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe that DWP should fully commit to financing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Jam-Jar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> accounts in the early years of Universal Credit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as this will increase both access to and awareness of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by many vulnerable and low-income households</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many landlords </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who specialise in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Local Housing Allowance (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">LHA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> market at the moment have built up good relations with key Housing Benefit staff in local authorit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ies. Under Universal Credit, decisions will be taken through on-line applications and central call-centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Therefore, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">essential local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">link</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s will be lost and as a result local authority based</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Tenancy Relations Officers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are of vital importance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Such staff in local authorities can act as impartial arbiters should problems with a tenancy arise in order to avoid tenancy breakdown and the need for landlords to seek possession. Unfortunately, many local authorities have withdrawn these services as a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> result of the recent austerity cuts and therefore DWP should consider funding at least one officer in each local authority to undertake this function; especially to act as a liaison </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">point </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">between landlord tenant and DWP.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is also important to highlight</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the good work done by many Private Sector Leasing Schemes (PSLSs) and Social Lettings Agencies (SLAs) in providing avenues for tenants on benefits to access good quality, affordable private rented housing. One of the ways </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">they</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are currently undertaking th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is task is by offerin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g direct payment to landlords </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who are willing to let their properties through these schemes. The introduction of Universal Credit will prevent such schemes from being able to offer this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">option</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and therefore removing the key </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t differentiate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> them from high street letting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">agents. The changes to Universal Credit are therefore likely to have a detrimental impact on the number of landlords willing to engage with such schemes.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">uestion 2(a):</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> The implications of the changes for land</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">lords (private rented sector only)</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The key concern for landlords with the creation of Universal Credit centres on the removal of the ‘secure or maintain’ provisions of the 2010 Statutory Instrument allowing landlords to get direct payment of LHA</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The remo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">val of this provision is likely to see an increase in the number of tenants falling into arrears (as has been the case in the Direct Payment Demonstration Projects). In turn, higher arrears will result in higher incidents of landlords seeking possession. I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t is also likely to result in landlords offering the shortest possible tenancies (six-months) in order to avoid significant losses from tenants falling into arrears and landlords being unable to begin possession proceedings until the end of the tenancy’s f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ixed period.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, it is also important to note that many of the problems with direct payment to tenants under LHA have been resolved under Universal Credit. In particular, the Third-Party Deductions from Benefits will be available to landlords for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tenants who have fallen into arrears. This will have a positive impact on landlords who, in the past, have had to write-off these arrears. However, these third party deductions might have a negative impact on the tenant’s ability to make future rental pay</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ments and may inadvertently cause a cyclical problem with rent arrears.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question 3:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> The treatment of housing costs within Universal Credit</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NLA would like to raise concerns over the impact of the benefits cap and its effect on the housing element of Un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iversal Credit. It will be a particular problem in areas such as London and the South-East and is likely to result in many claimants being unable to locate suitable housing in these regions. This is either going to result in a steady increase in arrears or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> force tenants to re-locate; potentially to different regions of the country.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We welcome the Alternative Payment Arrangements (APAs) that were announced by DWP in February 2013</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and expect the Housing Costs APA to be used the most. As is suggested in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">document we would argue that landlords should be allowed to notify DWP of any pre-existing business knowledge about a tenant’s rent arrears; rather than DWP only taking information from government agencies.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Several local authorities, such as Gateshead Coun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cil, currently operate “Traffic Light” schemes whereby landlords are informed before signing a tenancy that the tenants either has no history of rent arrears or anti-social behaviour ‘Green’; some incidents of either</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rent arrears or anti-social behaviour ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Amber’; or incidents of both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rent arrears and anti-social behaviour ‘Red’. This type of prior knowledge has meant that landlords know that a tenancy will require more active management before the tenancy commences which, in turn, reduces the likelihood of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tenancy breakdown. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, we will also highlight a problem with the arrears trigger. It is currently proposed that the trigger will set at tw</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o contractual months in arrears.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his will result in every Universal Credit recipient hitting the trigger befor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e they receive their first payment of Universal Credit. This is because the first payment of Universal Credit will be five weeks after the initial claim. For example, if the claim is made on 1 January 2014, the first payment will be 8 February 2013. If the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tenant moved into the property on 1 January 2013, by the time of the first payment (8 February), the tenant will already be more than two contractual months in arrears. DWP has not realised this massive problem. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is also important </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to note </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re likely to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be some claimants who </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">may</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> never be suitable for direct payment under Universal Credit and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">may</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> need to be on APAs continuously.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> The Housing benefit (Amendment) Regulations 2010 No. 2835</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Universal Credit: Guidance on personal budgeting support, DWP, 11 February 2013; Available at: </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/181400/personal-budgeting-support-guidance.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/181400/personal-budgeting-support-guidance.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p></body></html>